<title>Kristin Hansen, Assistant Press Secretary</title>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff">

<center>
<img src="/townhall/FRC/whois/whois.gif">
</center>

<p>

<center>

<h2><font size=+3>K</font>ristin <font size=+3>H</font>ansen</h2>

<h3>Assistant Press Secretary</h3>

<p><hr size=3 width=65%><p>
<img src="/townhall/FRC/photos/frc6.gif">
<p><hr size=3 width=65%><p>

</center>

In 1994, Miss Hansen joined the Family Research Council's Media
Department to facilitate the networking of information between
television, print, and radio contacts and FRC's Policy Experts.
Hansen's communication skills are a factor in FRC's rapidly growing
media presence in Washington, D.C. and nation-wide. 

<p>

Her responsibilities at FRC include handling all broadcast media
requests in the area of news and talk radio as well as planning
outgoing radio tours of FRC policy experts. In addition, Hansen
associates with television and print contacts along with the Director
of Communications in order to clearly present FRC's pro-family
message far and wide. As an effective spokesperson on politics,
policy, and the media, Hansen helps FRC in generating up to a
thousand clips a month and daily broadcast interviews.  

<p>

Hansen also works extensively on the media strategy for FRC's
special projects, such as the &quot;Save Sex&quot; campaign, 
<I>Let Freedom Ring: A Basic Outline of American History</I>, <I>The
Children of Table 34</I> video, and <I>A Family Fourth: Independence
Day and Other Celebrations</I>.

<p>

Hansen's experience includes work in a sports marketing firm
and in the development of athletic ministries. Native of Southern
California, Hansen graduated from Princeton University in 1994
receiving a Bachelor of Arts degree in English.

<p><HR SIZE = 3 WIDTH = 60%><p>

