<center>

<h2><font size=+3>C</font>harles <font size=+3>A.</font> 
<font size=+3>D</font>onovan</h2>

<h3>Senior Policy Advisor & Editor, <I>Washington Watch</I></h3>

<p><hr size=3 width=65%><p>
<img src="/townhall/FRC/photos/frc7.gif">
<p><hr size=3 width=65%><p>

</center>

<A HREF="/townhall/FRC/whois/donodoc.html">A Testimony by Charles 
A. Donovan</A>

<p>

Mr. Donovan is Senior Policy Adviser at the Family Research 
Council, a Washington-based education, research and public 
policy organization.  He is also the editor of the Council's 
monthly newsletter, <A HREF="/townhall/FRC/wwatch/wwnews.html">Washington 
Watch.</A>

<p>

Prior to joining FRC in February 1989, he served as Deputy Director 
of Presidential Correspondence at the White House beginning in 
1983.  He joined the Office of Presidential Correspondence as a 
writer/editor in April 1981.  From 1978 through 1981, he was 
Legislative Director in the Washington office of the National Right 
to Life Committee.  He has extensive experience as an 
editor/commentator:  He has appeared on ABC's "Nightline," CNN, CBN, 
the USA Radio Network and numerous other programs, and his writing 
has appeared in dozens of publications, including <I>USA Today</I>, 
the <I>Wall Street Journal</I>, the <I>Washington Times</I>, the 
<I>San Diego Union</I>, the Gannett and Scripps-Howard News Services, 
the <I>American Legion Magazine</I>, the journal <I>First Things</I>, 
and the <I>Cincinnati Enquirer</I>.

<p>

Mr. Donovan has also spoken widely, addressing audiences across the 
United States, in Canada, and overseas.  He presented a paper before 
the International Congress on the Family, Brighton, England in 1990, 
and served as a participant in a conference on family break-up at 
Rockford, Illinois, in 1989.  Donovan addressed the National 
Legislators Conference sponsored by Americans United for Life in 
Chicago in 1989.  He has testified before a Senate Appropriations 
Subcommittee and the Conservative Democratic Forum in the U.S. House 
of Representatives.

<p>

He has worked as a contributor to the sports pages of several 
publications and as an assistant in clean water research at the 
Taft Research Center of the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency in 
his native Cincinnati.

<p>

Mr. Donovan is co-author, with Robert G. Marshall, of <I>Blessed Are 
the Barren: A Social History of Planned Parenthood</I>(Ignatius 
Press, October 1991).  He is a 1974 graduate of the University of 
Notre Dame.  He and his wife Margaret have four children and reside 
in Bellingham, Massachusetts.

<p>

<p><HR SIZE = 3 WIDTH = 60%><p>

