<HEAD>

<TITLE>EDO 1996 Annual Meeting Report and Operational Review5 Annual Report:  Corporate Overview</TITLE>
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Kehoe, White, Savage & Company, Inc.">
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../gif/ir.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> </CENTER>
<H2><CENTER>1996 Annual Meeting Report<BR>and Operational Overview </CENTER></H2>

<H4><CENTER>April 23, 1996 </CENTER></H4>

<P>
<CENTER>[ <A HREF="../../secdocs.html">Investor Information and SEC Documents</A>
| <A HREF="../../irmenu.html">Investor Relations Home Page</A>
]</CENTER> 
<P>
<CENTER>[ <A HREF="../../prlsmenu.html">EDO News</A> | <A HREF="../../../index.html">EDO Corporation Home Page</A>
]</CENTER> <P><HR>

<P>
<H3>To Our Shareholders</H3>

At last year's annual meeting, I reported our first quarter of positive earnings in two years. I expressed my hope that this reflected only the early impact of our strategic plan to return the company to profitability and strong liquidity, and that we would continue improvement throughout the year.<P>

We did show steady improvement in 1995, and I am very pleased to announce that the first quarter of 1996 continued the trend. We recorded our fifth consecutive quarter of increased earnings.  Revenues for the first quarter were $26,281,000, up 25.6%, from the first quarter of 1995, while earnings were $650,000 or $0.11/share up from $0.02/share the first quarter of 1995. Backlog increased to $95,760,000, up 7.6%, from the first quarter of 1995. This increase in backlog reflects, principally, contracts received from Hughes Space and Communications Company and Barry Controls. Both these awards are from major prime contractors with whom we hope to share in the growth of these two solid and growing markets.<P>

Early in the first quarter, we concluded the sale of our College Point, New York property which eliminated significant idle fixed assets and reduced operating expenses. This will improve our future balance sheet and operating results, while paving the way for additional, planned, consolidation of our operations. Our first quarter cash balance of $26.3 million provides a strong reserve and resources to operate our current businesses without the need for borrowing. We announced today that our bank has agreed to additional favorable revisions to the terms of our lending instruments.<P>

Now, a few comments about 1995 operations.<P>

Since our 1995 annual report gives details on operations, I will today highlight only some significant points which impact our current and future situation. Most importantly, 1995 was a year for improvements in almost all of our businesses. While revenues for the year were up only 1% to $91.1 million, we recorded a net profit of $1.4 million or $0.25 per share, compared to a loss of $23.9 million or $4.30 per share in 1994.  We achieved our primary goal of returning the corporation to profitability.<P>

We also achieved our second major goal of improved liquidity. We funded operations with internally generated cash flow and ended 1995 with a cash balance up 42% to $25.6 million.<P>

In late 1995, our line of credit was increased from $5.0 million to $15.0 million. We appreciate the show of confidence by our bank and the excellent working relationship we have developed. While we do not anticipate drawing down on the line for operations, we increased it in anticipation of the need for letters of credit to cover advanced payments on international orders. <P>

In 1995, we increased our equity by approximately 32% to $14.2 million and market capitalization increased 58% to $29 million at year end. We hope that the continued increases in our market capitalization, since the end of 1995, reflect a growing investor awareness of the inherent worth of our company.<P>

Year-end 1995 backlog was up to $89.7 million, a 13% increase over the prior year.  As announced today, backlog continued to increase during the first quarter. We believe the current backlog, and anticipated orders in 1996, demonstrate the strength of our core businesses and validate our strategy.<P>

The defense segment of our business performed very well, capturing new programs in a very competitive and declining market, yielding profits, producing good cash flow, and improving its backlog of orders by 22%.<P>

We received development, production and logistic support contracts in our stores release and airborne mine countermeasures product lines which are the bulk of this backlog.<P>

The use of commercial off-the-shelf (known as "COTS") components in military systems has been embraced by the U. S. Department of Defense and is gaining international acceptance.  We believe that we are a leading company in the use of COTS for military systems, giving us a cost advantage over competition which uses equipment built to military specifications. We have already captured significant defense contracts for COTS-configured systems.<P>

In 1995, we completed the consolidation of the command and control and sonar systems product lines at our Chesapeake, Virginia facility. Co-locating these staffs has facilitated our ability to offer a cost-effective COTS combat system. We will begin international marketing of this internally funded system in 1996.<P>

Our position as a market leader in satellite earth sensors was expanded, in 1995, with the award of a contract from Daimler-Benz Aerospace for sensors used on the Loral "Globalstar" cellular communication satellite. This important win adds another major satellite constellation to the already impressive list of satellites which depend on EDO sensors for attitude control. Consistent with our long-term strategy of expanding our market to related satellite navigation systems, this contract also includes the development of a new sun sensor.<P>

A major turning point, in 1995, was the turnaround in our space business. This business, which has been a financial drain in the past, improved significantly. With the completion of the most difficult development programs in 1995, we are entering the production phase in 1996. The concurrent transition to production of several programs will present a significant management challenge in 1996. We are giving a great deal of management attention to this challenge.<P>

Our program, to supply Doppler speedometers for use on New York City subways, has been a success.  In late 1995, we received a contract for additional speedometers, closely followed in the first quarter of 1996 by an additional order to round out the remaining New York City subway market. We believe the basic speedometer technology complements other ground transportation products being developed by our industrial products division, and intend to attack this market in an integrated fashion.<P>

We have selected, as a target  market, vibration control in precision applications, where EDO's proprietary piezo-electric actuator technology is critical to success.  We received contracts for actuators for Barry Controls' STACIS 2000 active vibration cancellation table for the semiconductor market. The STACIS 2000 is enjoying increased customer acceptance. We are seeing a corresponding increase in orders, which hopefully will continue to grow.<P>

In cooperation with a machine tool manufacturer in 1995, we proved the concept of active vibration control on a precision cylindrical grinder. When development is completed, this new product will result in considerable savings to the end user. We expect to introduce a product in late 1996 or early 1997.<P>

EDO is a leading supplier of quality acoustic products to the world's defense and commercial markets.  In 1995, we were awarded a contract from Westinghouse for additional transducer assemblies for the U. S. Navy's primary anti-submarine warfare sensor.  Additionally, we were recently awarded orders from both Magnavox and Spartan for ceramic assemblies.<P>

We continued to be a leading supplier of water and waste tanks to commercial airlines, and are particularly proud to be a primary supplier of water and waste tanks for all the major Boeing aircraft, including waste tanks for the newest technology 737 series.<P>

In early 1996, we began production deliveries of wind blades for an international customer. These blades will be used on wind farms which "harvest" wind energy to produce electrical power. This environmentally friendly energy source should see an increasing market as greater emphasis is placed on cleaning the environment around the world.<P>

As part of our initiative to apply composite technology to the ground transportation market, we have formed a strategic alliance with Ingersoll-Rand, a leading supplier of large truck and bus air starter systems. As part of their system, Ingersoll-Rand will market our lightweight, corrosion resistant pressure vessel. We have just received an increased commitment, from Ingersoll-Rand, for more pressure vessels. In 1996, our composite brake cylinders will be tested on a major railroad's freight cars. We believe that composites have many potential applications in ground transportation. We plan to approach this market with partners who already have established positions. <P>

We have maintained our presence in the compressed natural gas fuel storage and infrastructure market, even though it has been developing very slowly. An increasing number of customers are recognizing the significant advantages of the EDO LiteRider natural gas fuel tank. We have increased our share of the load sensitive vehicle market typified by natural gas buses.<P>

In 1995, we formed a strategic marketing and technology alliance with three Japanese firms who purchased an equity interest in EDO Canada, Ltd. This alliance will strengthen our marketing and technical presence with Asian auto and bus manufacturers and enhance our ability to expand to other areas of the region. <P>

We are pursuing various natural gas vehicle fleet opportunities. For example: we are currently funded to configure New York City taxis as natural gas fueled vehicles.  In the first quarter of 1996, we received a contract from the new York state energy research and development authority for a program to develop a hybrid natural gas and electric powered vehicle, which should have application to the taxi and short range delivery market.<P>

With original equipment manufacturers, we are: under contract from Chrysler, to develop fuel tanks for their Cirrus natural gas vehicle; cooperating with General Motors on their test program to select a fuel tank for their small passenger vehicle; and are performing, under contract with an international OEM, a test program which we hope will lead to a production decision in 1996.<P>

Sales of our natural gas infra-structure related products, such as  compressor stations, are developing more slowly. While we are well positioned to exploit this market when it develops, because of its slow growth, we are moderating our investment.<P>

What's ahead?<P>

In this period of mega-mergers what has worked for EDO is a basic strategy of positioning ourselves as suppliers to major customers in the defense, space and commercial markets. We plan to continue to provide these large customers with high quality, specialty niche products, which are more cost effective to buy from us than to develop and produce themselves.<P>

Throughout this presentation and our annual report, we have referenced strategic alliances and partnerships. This proven method of leveraging our technology with complementary technical, production or marketing expertise of others, is a key feature of our future plans.<P>

In 1996, we will continue to emphasize profitability and liquidity. However, we believe that we must use our financial means and management resources to emphasize the revenue growth element of our strategic plan. By operating profitably with positive cash flow, our continuing core businesses will be the foundation of our future, by funding internal growth. We also plan to pursue additional revenue growth through acquisitions. We hope that by continuing to demonstrate prudent assets management, while willing to take reasonable risks, we will be able to attract additional capital from outside sources for prudent acquisitions consistent with our technical, management and market skills.<P>

We are optimistic about the future of our corporation. Our optimism is based on results. In 1995, we went back to basics and succeeded in creating a firm foundation of improved operations, increased backlog and a sound management team. So far, in 1996, we have continued our steady growth proving that we have a strong company, capable of performing in today's complex business environment.<P>

The results of the past year have been very encouraging, and personally satisfying, for all of us on the EDO team. A special word of appreciation from management and the  shareholders is due to all the dedicated people of EDO who have produced these results.<P>

Also, on behalf of all of your management and board of directors, may I express our appreciation for the loyalty and support of our long term shareholders and welcome the new shareholders who have recently joined us. We assure you all that we appreciate the confidence you have displayed by your investment in our corporation, and we are dedicated to further increasing shareholder value.<P>

Thank you for your attention.<P>

<B>Frank A. Fariello</B><BR>President and Chief Executive Officer

<P>
<HR>

