<HEAD>
  <META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Kehoe, White, Savage &amp; Company, Inc.">
  <TITLE>Press Release: EDO Corporation Reports FY96 Third Quarter Results </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P>
<Center>
<I><B>Press Release</B></I>
<P ALIGN=Center>
<IMG SRC="../../gif/edologo.gif">
<P>
[ <A HREF="../prlsmenu.html">List of Press Releases</A> |
<A HREF="../irmenu.html">Investor Relations Home Page</A> |
<A HREF="../../index.html">EDO Corporation Home Page</A> ]
  <HR>
<H2>
   EDO Corporation Reports<BR>Third Quarter Results </CENTER>
</H2>
<P>
COLLEGE POINT, NY  OCTOBER 23, 1996  EDO Corporation (NYSE:EDO) today reported net income for the third quarter period ended September 28, 1996 of $842,000, or $0.14 per share after the net effect of a $7.6 million provision for a loss on the discontinuance of the Company's participation in its energy related operations, including provision for operating losses during the phase out period, and a $7.1 million gain from the curtailment of post-retirement healthcare benefits for Medicare eligible retirees.  In the comparable 1995 period, EDO reported net income of $477,000, or $0.08 per share.<P>

Earnings from continuing operations before taxes in the 1996 third quarter increased 25% to $1,867,000, before the aforementioned $7.1 million gain, from $1,495,000 earned in the same period a year ago.  Sales from continuing operations for the 1996 third quarter increased 24% to $23,107,000 from $18,634,000 reported in the similar period a year ago.<P>

For the first nine months of 1996, EDO reported net income of $2,242,000, or $.37 per share after the above noted special items, compared to $869,000, or $0.15 per share, reported a year ago.  Earnings from continuing operations before taxes in the 1996 first nine months increased 38% to $5,277,000, before the aforementioned $7.1 million gain, from $3,811,000 earned in the same period a year ago.  Sales from continuing operations for the first nine months of 1996 increased 22% to $71,547,000 from $58,461,000 in the prior year.<P>

The Company's order backlog from continuing operations decreased to $81,754,000 at September 28, 1996 from $87,345,000 reported in the third quarter a year ago.  The decline stems principally from timing delays in the receipt of certain contracts, including a major contract from an international customer received after the quarter ended and disclosed in an October 21, 1996 press release.  Backlog as of October 21, 1996 was approximately $101 million. The backlog reported for the third quarter includes follow-on orders under long-term contracts for Mk 105 Airborne Mine Countermeasures System Upgrade Kits for the U. S. Navy, F-15E Bomb Release Units for the U.S. Air Force and piezo-ceramic elements for the Sparton and Magnavox sonobuoy programs.<P>

Frank A. Fariello, President and Chief Executive Officer, stated:  "Our third quarter results shows a continuation of improved operations.  The results reflect the fact that EDO is a strong, technology rich company that offers the potential for tangible growth in today's business environment. In order to maximize the return to our shareholders, our current strategic plan concentrates our resources on those core businesses which have been growing and increasing in profitability. The implementation of our plan also includes growing the company by internal funding of new products and aggressively pursuing new and complementary products through selective acquisition.<P>

"Consistent with our plan, we have sold our Seaplane Float operations and are in the process of selling an instrument product line.  We are very disappointed in having to discontinue our participation in the alternative fuels market, since we believe that it will be viable over the long term. However, the business does not meet our current strategic criteria.  Our energy businesses will continue to operate as before, while we seek financially sound investors who will be committed to the long term continuation of the businesses."<P>

Mr. Fariello continued:  "Our decision to discontinue medical benefits for our Medicare-eligible retirees reflects the popularity of Medicare HMOs, and the success of converting retirees' health coverage to such plans.  EDO had been encouraging Medicare-eligible retirees to join these HMOs because they typically are less costly to these retirees while also providing more services."<P>

EDO is principally a supplier of proprietary advanced electro-optical, electronic, mechanical, acoustic and composite products to major prime defense contractors and commercial original equipment manufacturers.  EDO also serves the domestic and international defense markets as a prime contractor for military systems.<P>

<B><I>NOTE:</I></B> Press releases and other EDO information are available
on the EDO Corporation world wide web site: http://www.edocorp.com.
<P>

