<HEAD>

<TITLE>Press Release: EDO Corporation Awarded Additional Contract, Valued at $8.1 Million, by U.S. Navy for Mk 105 Airborne Mine Countermeasures (AMCM)  System Upgrade Kits </TITLE>
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Kehoe, White, Savage & Company, Inc.">

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<P><CENTER><I><B>Press Release</B></I></CENTER><P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../gif/edologo.gif"> </CENTER>
<P ALIGN=Center>[ <A HREF="../prlsmenu.html">List of Press Releases</A> | <A HREF="../irmenu.html">Investor Relations Home Page</A> | <A HREF="../../index.html">EDO Corporation Home Page</A> ]<P><HR><P>

<H2><CENTER> EDO Corporation <BR> Awarded Additional Contract, <BR>Valued at $8.1 Million,<BR>by U.S. Navy for<BR>Mk 105 Airborne Mine<BR>Countermeasures (AMCM)  System<BR>Upgrade Kits</CENTER></H2><P>

COLLEGE POINT, NY  July 29, 1996    EDO Corporation (NYSE:EDO) announced today it has been awarded an additional contract, valued at $8.1 million, by the Department of the Navy for Mod 4 Upgrade Kits for the U. S. Navy's Mk 105 Airborne Mine Countermeasure (AMCM) Systems.<P>
The contract will be performed by EDO's Marine and Aircraft Systems business unit, located in College Point, New York, with deliveries starting early in 1998.  The U.S. Navy plans to purchase additional Mod. 4 Upgrade Kits for incorporation into its Mk 105 AMCM Systems over the next few years.  Depending on budget constraints, the total potential upgrade market, including logistics, could be significant.<P>
The Mod. 4 Upgrade provides a significant improvement to the maintainability, reliability and performance capabilities of the Mk 105 AMCM System.  The Mk 105 AMCM System is towed through the water by the MH-53 helicopter, and generates a magnetic field which explodes mines.  This system has been in service in the U.S. Navy since the early 1970s and is also in service in an international Navy.  <P>
Frank A. Fariello, President and Chief Executive Officer of EDO Corporation, stated:  "EDO, one of the world's leaders in the design, development and production of mine counter measure systems,  is committed to aggressively supporting the U.S. Navy's airborne mine countermeasures efforts.  In addition to this new contract award, we received approximately $16 million in contracts from the U.S. Navy during the past 12 months for Mk 105 Mod. 4 engineering work, Mod. 4 Upgrade Kits production and logistics support."<P>
Principally a designer and manufacturer of advanced electronic, mechanical, acoustic and composite products for military, space, marine and commercial aviation markets, EDO Corporation continues to pursue the application of its sophisticated and diverse technologies to new commercial and industrial markets.<P>
<B><I>"Safe Harbor" Statement under the Private Securities Litigation Reform Act of 1995:  </I></B>The statements in this Press Release relating to plans, strategies, economic performance and trends and other statements that are not descriptions of historical facts may be forward-looking statements within the meaning of the Private Securities Litigation Reform Act of 1995, Section 27A of the Securities Act of 1933 and Section 21E of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934.  Forward-looking information is inherently subject to risks and uncertainties, and actual results could differ materially from those currently anticipated due to a number of factors, which include, but are not limited to, U.S. and international military budget constraints and determinations, congressional discretion, U.S. and international government administration policies and priorities, changing military strategies, changes in government procurement strategies and practices and the general state of world military readiness and deployment.  The Company has no obligation to update these forward-looking statements.<P>
<I>NOTE:</I>  Press releases and other EDO information are available on the EDO Corporation World Wide Web site:  http://www.edocorp.com.
