<HEAD>

<TITLE>Press Release: EDO Corporation Announces Receipt of New York City Subway Speedometer Contracts Totaling $1,222,954 From The New York City Transit Authority </TITLE>
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Kehoe, White, Savage & Company, Inc.">

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<P><CENTER><I><B>Press Release</B></I></CENTER><P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../gif/edologo.gif"> </CENTER>
<P ALIGN=Center>[ <A HREF="../prlsmenu.html">List of Press Releases</A> | <A HREF="../irmenu.html">Investor Relations Home Page</A> | <A HREF="../../index.html">EDO Corporation Home Page</A> ]<P><HR><P>

<H2><CENTER>EDO Corporation Announces Receipt of<BR>New York City Subway Speedometer Contracts<BR>Totaling $1,222,954 From The<BR>New York City Transit Authority 
</CENTER></H2><P>

COLLEGE POINT, NY -- May 13, 1996 -- EDO Corporation (NYSE:EDO) today announced that its Marine and Aircraft Systems business unit was awarded two contracts by the New York City Transit Authority (NYCTA) totaling $1,222,954.  The contracts cover the production of 1,768 Speed Indicator Units (SIUs) which will be installed on New York City subway cars and will bring the total number of EDO SIUs on the New York City subway system to over 3,500.  The NYCTA plans to equip the remainder of its subway cars with speed indicator systems within the next few years.
<P>
EDO's SIU is a state-of-the-art, high technology "Doppler" system which utilizes electronics and signal processing experience developed by EDO as part of its defense product lines.  The Doppler SIU emits a low-power detection beam which is directed ahead and down to the track bed.  A portion of the radiated beam is reflected back to the sensor.  The frequency of the reflected signal is shifted by an amount proportional to the speed of the train relative to the track bed.  Once the sensor receives the reflected signal, a signal processor converts the signal into a two-digit, miles per hour speed indication.  The new SIU is extremely accurate, whether the train is accelerating, decelerating, or moving forward or in reverse.  In addition, the new SIUs are unaffected by slippage of subway car wheels or changes in wheel diameter.
<P>
Frank A. Fariello, President and Chief Executive Officer of EDO Corporation, stated:  "During the past 24 months, EDO has received approximately $3.5 million in contracts for the NYCTA for Speed Indicator Units and Conductor's Emergency Valve Alarms.  These contracts represent an example of the Company's ongoing business diversification efforts.  We will continue to utilize our defense electronics and mechanical systems expertise in the commercial marketplace."
<P>
Principally a designer and manufacturer of advanced electronic, mechanical, acoustic and composite products for military, space, marine and commercial aviation markets, EDO Corporation continues to pursue the application of its sophisticated and diverse technologies to new commercial and industrial markets.

NOTE:  Press releases and other EDO information are available on the EDO Corporation World Wide Web site:  http://www.edocorp.com.
<P><P>

